{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d579c0dd-2dc0-457e-8599-7ce34f852306","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01MzqwKxwcTBC43wX9BS2dQZ","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Enabling test hot reload"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_014ZWyZZoCraHGewTMkVEnMn","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-e0c97d249c1a4984944d5b4bd73b89a7/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>","new_str":"    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n    <TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>true</TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-e0c97d249c1a4984944d5b4bd73b89a7/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"130b6769-42a8-468c-bf62-8b8873cd361e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to enable hot reload for their .NET test project. With `dotnet test`, hot reload is enabled via `dotnet test --hotreload` or by setting `DOTNET_WATCH` or using `dotnet watch test`. But since they're using the newer testing platform (`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`), the hot reload feature for tests is done via `dotnet test --hotreload` which uses `TESTINGPLATFORM_HOTRELOAD_ENABLED` or similar.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. In .NET 9+, `dotnet test` supports hot reload via the `--hotreload` flag. To always enable it without setting an environment variable, the user can add an MSBuild property to their project file or create a `Directory.Build.props` file.\n\n\nFor the modern testing platform, I can set the `TestingPlatformHotReload` MSBuild property to enable hot reload by default, or the user could use `dotnet watch test` to automatically watch for changes. There are a few configuration approaches here—either through a `.runsettings` file, an MSBuild property, or `launchSettings.json`. should be `<TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>true</TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>` added to the project file. This enables the watch-and-rerun behavior automatically without needing the `--hotreload` flag each time. There are a few ways to enable hot reload for `dotnet test` — through environment variables like `DOTNET_WATCH` or `TESTINGPLATFORM_HOTRELOAD_ENABLED`, via `launchSettings.json`, or most cleanly through an MSBuild property in the `.csproj` file. I'm leaning toward `<TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>true</TestingPlatformHotReloadEnabled>` as the property name, though I'm not entirely certain of the exact mechanism the Microsoft.Testing.Platform uses to wire this up from the `--hotreload` CLI option.","outputTokens":1424,"requestId":"F81F:1B7339:5943022:612EC59:6A033776"},"id":"6de719a3-7f2d-46ad-b541-e4eb43d0358f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:22:09.707Z","parentId":"6ec3ad6f-d783-401c-a407-bcc1bb308bdf"}
